"Ballester J., Rodó X., Giorgi F.","Future changes in Central Europe heat waves expected to mostly follow summer mean warming",2010,"Climate Dynamics","35","7",,"1191","1205",,,10.1007/s00382-009-0641-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78649322971&partnerID=40&md5=fbb2f9a0f7cb281211dd3432cf65e548","Institut Català de Ciències del Clima (IC3), Carrer Dr. Trueta 203, 08005 Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain; Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy","Ballester, J., Institut Català de Ciències del Clima (IC3), Carrer Dr. Trueta 203, 08005 Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain; Rodó, X., Institut Català de Ciències del Clima (IC3), Carrer Dr. Trueta 203, 08005 Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain; Giorgi, F., Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics, Trieste, Italy","Daily output from the PRUDENCE ensemble of regional climate simulations for the end of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries over Europe is used to show that the increasing intensity of the most damaging summer heat waves over Central Europe is mostly due to higher base summer temperatures. In this context, base temperature is defined as the mean of the seasonal cycle component for those calendar days when regional heat waves occur and is close, albeit not identical, to the mean temperature for July-August. Although 36-47% of future Central Europe July and August days at the end of the twenty-first century are projected to be extreme according to the present day climatology, specific changes in deseasonalized heat wave anomalies are projected to be relatively small. Instead, changes in summer base temperatures appear much larger, clearly identifiable and of the same order of magnitude as changes in the whole magnitude of heat waves. Our results bear important consequences for the predictability of central European heat wave intensity under global warming conditions. © 2009 Springer-Verlag.","Climate change; Deseasonalized temperature anomalies; Heat wave; Multi-model ensemble; Regional Climate Model; Temperature seasonal cycle","air temperature; climate change; climate modeling; global warming; heat flux; regional climate; seasonal variation; summer; temperature anomaly; twenty first century; Central Europe",,,,,,"Alexander, L.V., Arblaster, J.M., Assessing trends in observed and modelled climate extremes over Australia in relation to future projections (2008) Int J Climatol, , doi: 10. 1002/joc. 1730; Ballester, J., Douville, H., Chauvin, F., Present-day climatology and projected changes of warm and cold days in the CNRM-CM3 global climate model (2009) Clim Dyn, 32, pp. 35-54; Barnett, D.N., Brown, S.J., Murphy, J.M., Sexton, D.M.H., Webb, M.J., Quantifying uncertainty in changes in extreme event frequency in response to doubled CO2 using a large ensemble of GCM simulations (2006) Clim Dyn, 26, pp. 489-511; Beniston, M., The 2003 heat wave in Europe: a shape of things to come? An analysis based on Swiss climatological data and model simulations (2004) Geophys Res Lett, 31, pp. L02202. , doi:10.1029/2003GL018857; Beniston, M., Diaz, H.F., The 2003 heat wave as an example of summers in a greenhouse climate? Observations and climate model simulations for Basel, Switzerland (2004) Glob Planet Change, 44, pp. 73-81; Black, E., Blackburn, M., Harrison, G., Hoskins, B., Methven, J., Factors contributing to the summer 2003 European heatwave (2004) Weather, 59, pp. 217-223; Box, J.E., Rinke, A., Evaluation of Greenland ice sheet surface climate in the HIRHAM Regional Climate Model using automatic weather station data (2002) J Clim, 16, pp. 1302-1319; Christensen, J.H., Carter, T.R., Giorgi, F., PRUDENCE employs new methods to assess European climate change (2002) Eos, 83, p. 147; Christensen, J.H., Carter, T.R., Rummukainen, M., Amanatidis, G., Evaluating the performance and utility of Regional Climate Models: the PRUDENCE project (2007) Clim Change, 81, pp. 1-6; Christensen, J.H., Boberg, F., Christensen, O.B., Lucas-Picher, P., On